  "prompt": "Do I essentially have to be valedictorian to be accepted into an elite university like Stanford or Harvard?",
  "response": "No, being valedictorian is not a requirement for acceptance into elite universities like Stanford or Harvard. While having a high class rank can be a strong indicator of academic excellence, these universities consider a wide range of factors in their holistic admissions processes. Here\u2019s what they typically look for:\n\n1. **Academic Excellence**: Strong grades in challenging courses (e.g., AP, IB, or honors classes) are important, but you don\u2019t need to be valedictorian. Demonstrating intellectual curiosity and a commitment to learning matters more than class rank alone.\n\n2. **Standardized Test Scores**: High SAT or ACT scores can strengthen your application, though some schools have test-optional policies.\n\n3. **Extracurricular Activities**: Leadership, passion, and impact in activities outside the classroom are highly valued. Depth and commitment are often more important than sheer quantity.\n\n4. **Essays**: Personal statements and supplemental essays provide an opportunity to showcase your personality, values, and unique perspective.\n\n5. **Letters of Recommendation**: Strong recommendations from teachers or mentors who can speak to your character, work ethic, and potential are important.\n\n6. **Demonstrated Interest**: Some schools consider how interested you are in attending their institution, though this varies by school.\n\n7. **Special Talents or Achievements**: Exceptional accomplishments in areas like research, athletics, arts, or community service can set you apart.\n\n8. **Background and Context**: Admissions officers consider adversity you\u2019ve overcome, your personal background, and the opportunities available to you.\n\nWhile being valedictorian can be a positive factor, many successful applicants are not ranked at the very top of their class. Instead, they demonstrate a combination of academic rigor, personal growth, and unique contributions to their communities. Admissions at elite universities aim to build a diverse and dynamic class, so there\u2019s no single formula for acceptance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
